title: For Sale:  SIG 556 SWAT DOES NOT HAVE A FOLDING STOCK
postcontent:
$2400 OBO
SIG556 SWAT Like the SIG556, the SIG556 SWAT features the same high-performance two position adjustable gas piston operating rod system engineered by SIGs sister company Swiss Arms and marries it to a trigger housing that not only cuts the rifles weight by a pound but is designed to accept standard AR magazines. The SIG556 SWAT features a 16 military grade cold hammer forged barrel, chambered in 5.56mm NATO, with a twist rate of 1 in 7. The high performance flash suppressor provides enhanced flash reduction and features an ACME type thread for compatibility with select industry sound suppression devices. The flash suppressor retains a standard .5 x 28 TPI thread pattern, ensuring compatibility with after-market accessories. The vented tactical quad rail forearm is machined from aircraft grade aluminum alloy and hard coat anodized for durability. The quad rail features four integrated steel Picatinny rails for mounting a wide range of accessories. The Picatinny rail equipped receiver is made of high strength carbon steel with a durable wear-resistant Nitron finish. The rifle comes standard with the flip up combat front and rear sight system. The trigger housing is machined from an aircraft grade aluminum alloy forging with a hard-coat anodized finish designed to survive extreme conditions. The rifle comes equipped with a smooth two-stage trigger, ambidextrous safety and is designed to accept standard AR magazines. A 30-round magazine is supplied with each rifle. The rifle features the MAGPUL CTR Carbine Buttstock. This buttstock is adjustable for length of pull and features a unique locking mechanism that friction locks the stock to the receiver extension for zero movement. The ergonomically designed pistol grip features an integrated storage compartment. The rifle also includes the Grip-Light vertical forend grip which features a removable tactical LED flashlight and mounts directly to the quad rail forend.

Note: Images shown with optional sling swivels, and second magazine not included.

SIG 556 Rifle Wins NRA Tactical Gun of the Year 

Few semi-automatic rifles have captured the imagination of the shooting public like the SG 550 series. For years this legendary Swiss-made rifle has been restricted to law enforcement and military sales, where it has acquired a reputation for reliability, durability and accuracy. Now, SIG Sauer has developed a U.S. made version called the SIG 556 ... . So stated Shooting Editor Glenn Gilbert in Like a Swiss Watch (December 2007, p. 46).

Both 556 SWAT and full-length versions feature the quality shooters have come to expect from SIG, including steel Picatinny rails fixed to the tops of their receivers and military-grade cold-hammer-forged barrels. But these are fully updated designs. Significant changes have been made to the lower receiver and the stock. The cast aluminum lower receiver retains the ambidextrous safety lever of the original 550, but the magazine well has been modified to take commercial and surplus AR-15/M16-style magazines. Further, given the crisp break and limited overtravel of its trigger, the SIG 556s accuracy was commendable.

The bottom line, simply stated, wrote Gilbert, is that the SIG 556 is an exceptionally accurate and reliable semi-automatic rifle whose performance is more than enough to justify its existence. That shared sentiment among staffers resulted in the SIG Sauer 556 being named the first-ever American Rifleman Tactical Gun of the Year.

title: For Trade:  EAA Windicator .357 Magnum
postcontent:
I have an EAA Windicator in .357 magnum that I am looking to possibly trade for something else. 
I bought it this summer and it is in pretty good condition and comes with the box, lock, paperwork, and a speedloader.   These guns are surprisingly accurate for a 2inch snub and this one is no exception.  Absolutely nothing wrong with it, however I'm looking to see if I could find something lighter for concealed carry.  I like to ankle carry but this thing feels like a brick strapped to my leg and has been making me sore lately.  WOuld probably be better as an IWB gun, but I haven't bothered to try.  People keep asking, it IS a .357, the marking is right under the .38 special marking, if you zoom in on the picture you can see it.  I've also fired .357's out of it as well with no issues.

So, I'm wondering if someone would be willing to trade for something lighter weight that would be a bit more comfortable for carry.  I'm looking for another snub nosed .38 (It's a .357 but I never use them).  I prefer ones with an exposed hammer for single action use, but doesnt have to be.  Would really like an LCR .38, but I'm open to other options as well.  Would be a great choice if you're wanting to "upgrade" to a .357 magnum.  No Charter arms please.  Ftf only

I might also trade for a full sized (4-8in barrel) .357 for range use and hunting and so I can work on my handloads.
Might also be willing to trade for something in .45, but again, primarily looking for a wheelgun.  NO HI POINTS, already have one that I dont use.

title: For Sale/Trade:  mosin-nagant 91/30 PU sniper
postcontent:
**Reposting due to buyer never showing up and not getting back to me**

This is a Mosin-Nagant rifle (1943 Izhevsk) that was converted into a sniper. The scope, mount and the rifle are in excellent condition. Sure, it ain't an original sniper it is the closest you can get to one without buying the real thing. 

Includes over 60 rounds of 7.62x54R ammo (24 soft point hunting rounds and 40+ FMJ) and a bayonet

Looking to sell for cash but I might take trades if i'm interested in what you have. 

Email if you want more pictures, have questions, or if you want to buy it. 

Thanks for looking! 

questions that have been asked:

Q: Is the scope and mount original? 
A: I know it is Russian made and has all the features of a genuine PU scope (steel construction, german post reticle that moves in the field of view when adjusted, etc). However, it is in very good shape. Almost too good to have been from the  WWII era. There is no date stamped on it so I have no way of telling when it was made. One of my pictures shows the marking on the scope. I wish I could tell you more but that's all I really know about it. 

Q: Will you ship it to me? 
A: If you cover all the expenses and keep it legal yes. I'll need your FFL's contact info when you email me if you would like it shipped. After i discuss it with them I'll get back to you with the total price including the shipping and their fees. If it is shipped I'll accept postal money order only (no checks). The rifle will ship as soon as I recieve payment. 

Q: will you sell the scope and mount seperate?
A: yes if you make me a good enough offer for it. Keep in mind that is the most expensive part of this rifle so you'll have to offer the majority of my asking price for me to even consider it. 

Q: will you sell for cash or trade locally? 
A: yes. I will meet you in the Titusville, PA (16354) area. Only arrange to meet if you are serious and definitely going to buy the rifle. If you have questions not answered here fell free to email and ask. I won't waste time and gas to meet with you if you are not buying.
